When opening a new pull request I find it useful to use the URL that is suggested when pushing a new branch:

{{remote: Create pull request for BRANCH_NAME:}}
{{remote: [https://bitbucket.org/COMPANY/REPO/pull-requests/new?source=BRANCH_NAME&t=1]}}

This creates a new pull request targeted to the repository's default branch  We have one repository where the master and develop branches are wildly divergent.  It would be very useful to be able to specify the target branch name when creating the pr, e.g:

[https://bitbucket.org/COMPANY/REPO/pull-requests/new?source=BRANCH_NAME&t=1&targetBranch=master|https://bitbucket.org/COMPANY/REPO/pull-requests/new?source=BRANCH_NAME&t=1]

h3. Issue Summary

When attempting to create a repository in another user's personal workspace via API, it results with error:

 
{noformat}
{    
    "type": "error",
    "error": {
       "message": "You cannot administer personal accounts of other users."
    }
}{noformat}
Even though the same user can create a repository in the _same_ workspace via Bitbucket UI even when ensuring the user has proper permissions to create repositories in that workspace.

 
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Grant a user "Create" repository access to a personal workspace in bitbucket
 # Have that user attempt to create a repository in that workspace via Bitbucket UI (this should work as long as they have proper permissions)
 # Have that user then attempt to create a repository in the same workspace using [API|https://developer.atlassian.com/bitbucket/api/2/reference/resource/repositories/%7Bworkspace%7D/%7Brepo_slug%7D]  
 # Observe that they get an error

h3. Expected Results

The behavior should be consistent for both UI and API. (user should be able to create repositories in a personal workspace from both UI and API.
h3. Actual Results

User is able to create repository in the workspace via Bitbucket UI, but gets following error when attempting via API:
{noformat}
{ "type": "error", "error": { "message": "You cannot administer personal accounts of other users." } }
{noformat}
h3. Workaround

The only workaround would be to create a Team workspace instead, transferring all of the existing repositories to that team workspace, along with the users and settings, and then working out of the team workspace instead.

Please consider implementing the 1.0 API for archive that we had into API 2.0 

{code}
/rest/api/1.0/projects/{projectKey}/repos/{repositorySlug}/archive
{code}

Please consider setting this up in a way to specify a commit reference or tag reference, so that a user can provide the right version download in composer. Ideally, a format type system (similar to 1.0) would be helpful as well if this is implemented. 

Business Case: For a dynamic composer repository to work properly, the user needs to "proxy" the download to their customers and would like to fetch the archives from our environment (without resorting to taking clones).

h3. Issue Summary

For pagination of the pullrequests/activity API endpoint you should never supply a `page` query parameter. You should always use the `next` URL that is included in the API response. As the documentation states...

> Clients are not expected to construct URLs themselves by manipulating the page number query parameter. Instead, the response contains a link to the next page. This link should be treated as an opaque location that is not to be constructed by clients or even assumed to be predictable. The only contract around the next link is that it will return the next chunk of results.

This bug report is to add back support for a misbehaving client that has many installations that are not centrally upgradable. This bug report adds support for a page parameter to be used as an alternate method of paging through pull request activity results.
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 * Make an API call to the pullrequests/activity endpoint

{code:java}
$ curl -X GET -u username:password https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories/<workspace>/<repo_name>/pullrequests/activity?page=4 {code}
h3. Actual Results
{code:java}
"next": "https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories/<workspace>/<repo_name>/pullrequests/activity?ctx=kaF7IMCzur&page=4"{code}
h3.  Expected Results
{code:java}
"next": "https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories/<workspace>/<repo_name>/pullrequests/activity?ctx=kaF7IMCzur&page=5"  {code}

h3. Issue Summary

With ["*/2.0/teams/*" API endpoint deprecating on October 14, 2020|https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/bitbucket/bitbucket-api-teams-deprecation/], there's *no alternative endpoint* for users to run API to obtain a list of users who have access to repository.

Current endpoint to acheive the outcome, which will be deprecated on 14th October:
 *  "/2.0/teams/<username>/permissions/repositories/<RepoSlug>" - [Bitbucket API |https://developer.atlassian.com/bitbucket/api/2/reference/resource/teams/%7Busername%7D/permissions/repositories/%7Brepo_slug%7D]

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Replacing the existing API call from {{team}} to {{workspace}}
{code:java}
https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/workspace/<WorkspaceID>/permissions/repositories/<RepoSlug>
{code}

 # The endpoint will return the following error
{code:java}
{
  "type": "error",
  "error": {
    "message": "Resource not found",
    "detail": "There is no API hosted at this URL.\n\nFor information about our API's, please refer to the documentation at: https://developer.atlassian.com/bitbucket/api/2/reference/"
  }
}
{code}

h3. Expected Results

With the endpoints transition from "teams" to "workspaces", it's expected that both of the following endpoint will work the same:
{code:java}
https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/teams/<Username>/permissions/repositories/<RepoSlug>
https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/workspaces/<WorkspaceID>/permissions/repositories/<RepoSlug>
{code}
h3. Actual Results

The {{workspace}} endpoint returned the following error while calling "workspace/<WorkspaceID>/permissions/repositories" endpoint
{code:java}
{
  "type": "error",
  "error": {
    "message": "Resource not found",
    "detail": "There is no API hosted at this URL.\n\nFor information about our API's, please refer to the documentation at: https://developer.atlassian.com/bitbucket/api/2/reference/"
  }
}
{code}
h3. Workaround

No workaround
